data.chText: 柱子，桥墩（尤指兼作装饰的）
data.enText: a large round stone, metal or wooden post that is used to support a bridge, the roof of a building, etc., especially when it is also decorative
a large round stone, metal or wooden post that is built to remind people of a famous person or event
a mass of sth that is shaped like a pillar

data.chText: 台柱子；主心骨；中流砥柱
data.enText: a strong supporter of sth; an important member of sth

data.chText: 富有某种素质的人；某种素质的化身
data.enText: a person who has a lot of a particular quality

data.chText: 她在危难中表现非常坚强。
data.enText: She is a pillar of strength in a crisis.

data.chText: （组织、制度、信仰等的）核心，基础，支柱
data.enText: a basic part or feature of a system, organization, belief, etc.
the central pillar of this theory
be driven, pushed, etc. from pillar to post

data.chText: 被迫四处碰壁（或到处奔波）
data.enText: to be forced to go from one person or situation to another without achieving anything

tr: (architecture) a tall vertical cylindrical structure standing upright and used to support a structure
a vertical cylindrical structure standing alone and not supporting anything (such as a monument)

example: science eroded the pillars of superstition
he is a pillar of the community

tr: anything that approximates the shape of a column or tower
example: the test tube held a column of white powder
a tower of dust rose above the horizon
a thin pillar of smoke betrayed their campsite

value.def: A pillar is a tall solid structure, which is usually used to support part of a building.
If something is the pillar of a system or agreement, it is the most important part of it or what makes it strong and successful.

example.ex: The pillar of her economic policy was keeping tight control over money supply.
example.tran: 她经济政策的核心是严格控制货币的供应。
种族隔离制最后的支柱

value.def: If you describe someone as a pillar of society or as a pillar of the community, you approve of them because they play an important and active part in society or in the community.

example.ex: My father had been a pillar of the community.
example.tran: 我父亲一直是社区的顶梁柱。
